  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel paradigm called Proactive Strategic Data Augmentation via Meta-Learned Trajectory Forecasting (PSDA-MTF), a framework designed to improve the out-of-distribution generalization of Gin Rummy hand evaluation models by generating anticipatory training samples that simulate future strategic shifts in opponents. While existing methods focus on augmenting within observed strategy spaces, PSDA-MTF addresses a critical gap: real-world gameplay involves non-stationary dynamics where players adapt their tactics over time based on experience, win/loss feedback, or meta-game awareness. Standard augmentation fails here because it cannot simulate such temporal evolution. PSDA-MTF solves this by integrating three core innovations: (1) a temporal strategy manifold encoder that maps sequences of hands into evolving latent strategy trajectories using a continuous-time variational autoencoder (CT-VAE), capturing both current style and directional momentum (e.g., increasing aggression); (2) a meta-learned domain transformer that predicts plausible future states of these trajectories up to k steps ahead, trained via bi-level optimization to maximize validation performance under simulated strategy drift; and (3) a grammar-governed counterfactual generator that synthesizes legally valid hands aligned with forecasted strategies, ensuring structural integrity while enabling proactive learning. The augmentation process begins by segmenting gameplay logs into rolling windows of N consecutive hands per player, from which the CT-VAE infers a trajectory in strategy space. The meta-learner then optimizes transformation parameters to project this trajectory forward under various perturbation regimes (e.g., sudden shift to high-risk discards). For each forecasted point, the system generates multiple augmented hands using injective grammar rules conditioned on the predicted strategy vector, producing variants that represent what an opponent might do *next*, not